{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T12:13:49.689Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Causes — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Causes Vanishing and Exploding Gradients"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Vanishing and exploding gradients are mainly caused by "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "how gradients are repeatedly multiplied during backpropagation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", especially in deep networks and recurrent networks. When those repeated multipliers are mostly smaller than 1, gradients shrink toward zero; when they are mostly larger than 1, gradients grow uncontrollably."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Main Causes"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "1. Saturating activation functions"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Functions like "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "sigmoid"}, {"type": "text", "text": " and "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "tanh"}, {"type": "text", "text": " can cause gradients to vanish because their derivatives become very small in saturated regions. If a neuron is pushed into the flat part of the curve, backpropagation gets a tiny gradient and earlier layers learn very slowly or not at all."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "2. Deep network depth"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The deeper the network, the more times the gradient has to pass backward through layers, so small changes get multiplied many times. This repeated multiplication is what makes the problem grow exponentially with depth."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "3. Recurrent connections"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Recurrent neural networks are especially vulnerable because the "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "same weights are reused across many time steps"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", so the gradient is multiplied repeatedly through time as well as through layers. That is why long sequence modeling is so prone to vanishing or exploding gradients."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "4. Poor weight initialization"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "If weights are initialized "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "too small"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", activations and gradients tend to shrink as they propagate, which encourages vanishing gradients. If weights are initialized "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "too large"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", they can amplify signals and produce exploding gradients."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "5. High learning rates"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A learning rate that is too large can make parameter updates jump too far, which can destabilize training and contribute to exploding gradients. A very small learning rate can also make learning appear stalled, which can worsen the practical effect of vanishing gradients."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "6. Unscaled or poorly conditioned inputs"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Inputs with large or uneven scales can push activations into unstable ranges, which makes saturation and gradient instability more likely. This is why normalization and proper preprocessing often help."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Vanishing vs. Exploding"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Problem"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What happens"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Typical cause"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Vanishing gradients"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gradients become very small, close to zero"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Saturating activations, too-deep chains, small weights"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Exploding gradients"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gradients become very large and unstable"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Large weights, deep recurrence, high learning rates"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why This Happens Mathematically"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Backpropagation uses the chain rule, so each layer contributes a multiplier to the gradient. If the average multiplier is below 1, the product shrinks exponentially; if it is above 1, the product grows exponentially. That is the core reason these problems become severe in deep and recurrent architectures."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Generative AI Context"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In generative AI, these issues matter because sequence models need to preserve information over many steps. If gradients vanish, earlier tokens or layers stop learning useful long-range structure; if they explode, training can become unstable or diverge."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mental Model"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Think of backpropagation like sending a message through a long line of people. If each person whispers a little quieter than the last, the message disappears; if each person repeats it louder, it becomes chaotic. Vanishing gradients are the whispering problem, and exploding gradients are the shouting problem."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key Takeaways"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Vanishing and exploding gradients come from "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "repeated multiplication of gradients"}, {"type": "text", "text": " during backpropagation."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Sigmoid and tanh"}, {"type": "text", "text": " often cause vanishing gradients because their derivatives saturate near zero."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Deep networks"}, {"type": "text", "text": " make the problem worse because the gradient must pass through many layers."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "RNNs"}, {"type": "text", "text": " are especially vulnerable because the same weights are reused across many time steps."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Poor initialization"}, {"type": "text", "text": " can shrink or amplify gradients before training even starts."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "High learning rates"}, {"type": "text", "text": " can contribute to exploding gradients and unstable training."}]}]}]}]}}